reviewText: Strike Back Season 2 is an excellent follow-up to a great first season.  The show kept me on the edge of my seat and had one surprise after the other.  The acting and writing were top notch and adding Rhona Mitra to the cast was the perfect choice as she brought the show to a whole new level.  I'm looking forward to watching the 3rd season.
Any hints on the release date? UK is releasing by November 5 on DVD only. Will appreciate any other information you may have.

I watched this series on Cinemax this season and this show rocks.  After about 3 episodes I bought the 1st season.  It too rocks.  Lots of action, very entertaining and I recommend it highly if you like super secret, black bag ops type stuff.  I fully intend to buy the series on Blu-ray as soon as it comes out.  I'm am looking forward to season 3, I can't wait!

I gave this five stars because it's probably the funniest series I've ever watched. If you like clich, if you like predictability, and especially if you like to laughed out loud then this is the one for you. Comic book characters, writing that telegraph's, no shouts "here I come" and a pure unrealism that will have you rolling in the isles. Remember the old westerns where everybody shoots and only the "good guys" have silver bullets? Well, here it is come back to you from the past. The "bad guys" (hate that term) are black hatted and usually of the same skin color -- or at least with accents that leave no doubt -- and the good guys opposite. Seriously it's sooooo bad it's just funny, blood and all. C'mon suspend your need for realism and come on the blood stained, joy ride of your life. Like my old granny used to say; "if you stick it out it's bound to get cut off." Love and kisses, laughing guy.

My only complaint is sometimes the writing betrays their military consultant director and the cheese spreads.  Most of the time however, the military aspect is better and more believable than anything coming out of Hollywood these days.  You can tell the two lead actors care about learning the military technique. I want to see at least somewhat realistic action, and this fits that bill.  Great prop weapon armory, quick accurate shots, and proper CQB techniques, all make it fun to watch. I will say they fire full auto way too much, but I think that's just to ramp up the action.

Sometimes it can be kinda silly that the bad guys just murder their own constantly.  Any tiny infraction of a subordinate equals instant death, which is a hard punishment if you just put in 2 creams instead of 1 in the bosses coffee. It's a cheap way to villainize the antagonist, but that's not a deal breaker for me.

Read some info about this series. The actors trained with former SAS members, and it shows. The plot which takes ten episodes to play out is more complex than most shows. Highly recommended, binge worthy entertainment.

However, after watching 2 seasons, I find myself constantly asking myself the following:
1) How much did Ray Ban pay for the blatant nonstop product placement?
2) Does Damien Scott literally need to bang everything that moves?
3) Is it part of "terrorist school" to always run from a covered position to the middle of the room screaming and holding a AK waiting to get shot?

Strike Back returns to its high octane miliue, Sgt. Michael Stonbridge and Sgt. Damien Scott are on different paths and Section 20 is about to be disbanded. The series actors have great technical advisers which lets the action sequences ring true. One has to suspend belief during the fire fights since the bad guys can only score kills up close and personal while our Section 20 special operators can take out  hostiles at any distance; that said if your willing to sit back and enjoy this action series, you will understand why it was such a popular show. Scott and Stone are after nuclear triggers; a hunt that takes them round the world to various exotic locations ( which is another positive aspect of this series) The supporting characters are excellent with abundant roles for for strong females.( which all happen to be beautiful.) Hey! I did say that one had to suspend belief. Good use of the talents of Sgt. Julia Richmond ( Michelle Lukes) who this season gets to come out from behind the computers and utilize her deadly skills in taking down hostiles. One can only hope that she will survive to display her skills throughout series, this hard hitting series has more then once eliminated a central character. I can recommend this show but caution that the violence and the sex are explicit and  it often feels like a multiple shooter video game, still i haven't had so much fun this the "Unit" ended.

Awesome!  Love the Africa-centric storyline and action.  Real world plots filmed in beautiful exotic places, thrusting the viewer into issues of arms dealing, ethnic cleansing, drugs, and terrorism.  Scott and Stonebridge make a great team, as we watch these two 'operators' continue to learn how to work together in pursuit of their target.  Even though this was produced by the BBC, and shown here in the States on Cinemax, I've noticed that the nudity and graphic sex of Season 1 has been toned down as Scott seems to have 'matured' and begun seeking out more meaningful relationships instead of bedding every woman he sees.  Or the show producers have switched their strategy, preferring to emphasis story.  Either way, the action is exciting and often unpredictable.  Can't wait to watch Season 3!

There's sort of a comical amount of sex and nudity--a la "Skin-emax"--and I often refer to this as "that show about the handsome spy guys," but it's compelling, entertaining, and a good binge watch. I especially appreciate how authentic the military tactics seem. The way they hold their weapons, the way they move, strategize, proceed, curse, get injured, it seems more authentic than most TV depictions. The actors must have worked very hard to develop those skills. The writing is okay, but it's not the greatest draw of the show. There's a sort of A-team predictability about the arc of each season, and the writers tend to telegraph their passes, but that's okay. Production quality is high and the show, on the whole, is entertaining (especially if you like boobs, butts, explosions, car chases, and guns). I wish every season were available for free on Prime. I'll be waiting.

This series is very entertaining, especially if one can look beyond its more testosterone-laden aspects (frequent battleground hook-ups stretch one's suspension of disbelief to the absolute limit as far as I'm concerned).  The characters are interesting for the most part, and have been gradually developed over the first two seasons, although the depiction of Damien Scott as the brash, crude, tough-talking American borders on caricature.  The show's willingness to suddenly lose key characters at any time makes things less predictable than usual, so you never know who will survive and who will not (other than the two leads).  On the other hand, there is a laughable lack of accountability for the seemingly hundreds of native casualties that pile up whenever an assault occurs on foreign soil (how many bullets can these guns actually fire, and why are there so many bad guys with machine guns who never seem to be able to hit any of the Section 20 team?).  Regardless, the intensity of the show is high, the action is plentiful, and the production values are high.  The show knows exactly what it's here for -- entertainment -- and delivers it very well.

FANTASTIC series!!!!.'Strike Back' is one of the best series I've seen in a while...Action packed, great characters, acting, story lines, and the hot ladies are always welcome..The Brits really cranked out a good one with 'Strike Back'...The action shootout scenes/cinematography are incredible and better then 99% of comparable genre. A lot must of gone into the production of the big action scenes, as it looked much more realistic then a lot of crap out there..Stonebridge and Scott definitely missed being shot by a couple thousand rounds though, but they made it look good..The writer(s) surely had access to ex Delta,Seal, SAS, and similar top tier operators, as that what made these "6 million dollar soldiers" kick so much ass..I have no doubt that the U.S./UK spend a lot of $$$ to train the best of the best and it pays off..It took me a couple episodes to get into the show, but once I got into it, I was hooked and craving more..I binged watched Season 1 & 2 within a couple weeks and can't wait for Season 3 & 4 to be 'Prime available'...It's nice to watch an entertaining series without all the 'politically correct' nonsense that is in the majority of TV these days, especially in the U.S. The Brits let it all out...Amazon, bring on Season 3 & 4 ASAP!!!

This series just keeps getting better.  The evolving personal relationship between the two main characters, Michael Stonebridge and Daemon Scott, is central to the series.  The plot lines are right from today's headlines, though some of the gunfights are a bit over the top.  But it's entertainment - right?
And I used to think the sex scenes were gratuitous - they still are but - they are central to telling us more about Daemon.  Just enjoy the beauty of the moment.  If you get queasy, step out for a refill.

The sex portrayals are practically gratuitous and unnecessarily graphic. I'm constantly amazed at the seemingly immediate arousal and satisfaction of the female characters. The mechanics are pretty much the same too. While the action is totally engrossing the level of violence and its portrayal is also unnecessarily graphic. It needn't be so. Just look back at some early horror or action stories from Alfred Hitchcock. He leads you there and leaves you hanging and having to bridge that wondrous gap between imagination and reality. I really keep trying to pull myself out of the series and most probably will succeed fairly soon because my eyes pop or I have to look away at some really horrisome details best left unsaid. Enough is enough! (And yes I'm aware or the pre-show disclaimer)

Strike Back's characters are the kind of people you would either want on your side or want to be like. This show portrays a world of pure action-adventure fantasy. How it is created and produced makes its events and accompanying actions seem plausible in the real world. Its characters, on the other hand, approach being super-heroes. Yet that is a good thing. By identifying with either one of them a viewer's sense of wish-fulfillment reaches gratification. Who would not like to possess mental and physical comportment both male, main characters portray? Become immersed in the fantasy and a sense of gratification is achieved.

For anyone who loves frequent occurring big explosions; this is a series for you. For anyone who enjoys frequent and cool, well choreographed fire-fights; this series is for you. Just sit back in your chair, so to speak, watch Strike Back, which has its basis in old western films. the wild west this time, South Africa, and let your mind go on an action-adventure.

I put this show in drawer marked guilty pleasure. It's preposterous, but in a Bond-ian manner, the Daniel Craig Bond especially. Most of Season 2 was shot in South Africa. As a fan of South Africa who has officially promoted the country as a location, I like that. The action is unrelenting. The sex is graphic. As for the violence, well, this is not a show for Quakers.

This is entertaining.  The production is quite good, and there are many settings convincingly presented in different areas of the world.  The plot lines are interesting and current, without much regard to political correctness -- i.e. the fictional terrorists are strikingly similar to terrorists in the real world. The interplay between the two main characters -- mismatched, of course -- is fun, and continues to evolve from one episode to another.  The gunplay is frequent, and at times, most times really, is absurd.  The bad guys apparently do not aim, and also patiently wait their turn to be gunned down.  This happens at least twice an episode, sometimes more.  But this show's aim is entertainment, not enlightenment, so for those willing to suspend a fair amount of disbelief, it is worth a look.

The first season of "Strike Back" was a ten episode thrill ride.  I had little hope season two could match it or even come close.  I was wrong.  Season two is just as good as, if not better than, season one.  The pace is fast, the characters believable, and the violence almost numbing.  At times I thought I was watching a first person shooter video game, except I wasn't doing the shooting.  Despite all the endless violence, the writers somehow continue to develop the relationship between the two male leads as they become more trusting and dependent on each other to survive and accomplish the mission's end.  You don't expect these character developments amidst all the human carnage, but somehow it is accomplished.  As in season one, no one--no matter how central or tangential to the story line--has safe passage.  I have seen trailers for the fall 2015 TV season that indicate that both male leads have their own new series for American television.  I hope this doesn't mean there won't be a season three.

There are some good turns by Rhona Mitra as the new leader of Section 20 and Shane Taylor as a former soldier gone nutter. But I don't particularly like the more serious version of Scott and while I like Philip Winchester as an action actor, he simply can't play an effective grieving husband. I hope by Season 3 (4) the boys return to their usual selves!

The entertaining BBC/CinemaX series starts "good" and gets better with each episode: but Season 2 never really reaches greatness although the actors' accents have improved.

According to IMDB (Internet Movie Data Base), the "British" leading role (Sgt. Stonebridge) is played by an American and the American "Section 20" operator (Sgt. Scott) is played by an Australian: yet, they seem perfectly cast for their respective roles.

The American Section 20 operator apparently oozes some irresistible Marvel hero-like pheromones (is there a Pheromone Man?) as he beds nearly every woman in the show despite displaying the charm of a questionably sterile, but definitely cold, gynecological instrument.

If this carried a movie rating, it would most definitely be "NC-17" for the explicit sex scenes.

I'd rate this season 4.5 Stars or somewhere between "I Like It" and "I Love It" as the writing (at times) works a little too hard to be "cool": and, some of the military tactics/character choices seem questionable and inconsistent (e.g. expressly declaring not to shoot at a helicopter because it has a nuclear warhead on board in one episode but then shooting at a truck with the same type of nuclear warhead tied to the flatbed in a different episode).

For Fans of "The Unit", "MI-5", international special forces type film/TV, and soft-core, this series may be described as Seal Team Six meets "MI-5" with an injection of testosterone and plot thickening, "story-line essential", soft-core scenes in nearly every episode.

Military tactics application and execution rank near "The Unit" and seem about as realistic as TV drama permits given the notion that TV stars can neither be encumbered nor can they have their faces or pecs obstructed by standard military tactical gear - especially helmets (except for the pilot episode).

If you can overlook some of the minor inconsistencies, graphic sex and violence, the penchant for dropping F-bombs during chase and combat scenes, then you may find this series entertaining -- when in the mood for mindless action.

See Strike Back On IMBD here: http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1492179/?ref_=ttfc_fc_tt

I tried to get into this show - watched three seasons to really give it a shot.  The problem with this type of show is multifold (SPOILERS BELOW):

Despite all of the flying bullets, there's never any real tension because you know the leads will NEVER be seriously injured or killed.  The Richard Artmitage season was more about John Porter's wits and instinct than "soldiering," so it didn't need the redundant gun battles.

Yet, the entire season is basically "watch Section 20 be incredibly inept and reckless and beg the question of why this is supposed to be such an elite unit."  Both lead characters should be dead many times over, especially Damien Scott. And yes, this applies to the Project Dawn season as well.

I'm pretty sure I'm supposed to like Scott, but all I kept thinking was, "This dude would have been dishonorably discharged regardless of any conspiracy."  He's supposed to be the ladies' man, the "charismatic" one, yet Stonebridge (when given the chance) is much more effective when talking to others.

The genuinely interesting geopolitics are skimmed over in favor of incessant and pointless gunfights.  I was more interested in the Zimbabwean characters, particularly the father and daughter revolutionaries, than any of the personal conflicts of the leads. And the actor (Rhashan Stone) who played Sinclaire brought a sense of integrity and class to the show, so imagine my disappointment with his death.

In summary, the theme song and seeing Winchester shirtless are the best parts of the show.

Worked through the first two seasons of this in record time. Thoroughly enjoyable. Two-man expendables team travels the world kicking assets for British military intelligence. There's an over arching story thread for each season but my friends have been able to join me, jumping in at odd points, and enjoying the action, the tough as nails heroes, the camaraderie and the big hairy fiery explosions. Episodes generally unfold in twos, i.e. one culminating in a cliffhanger that becomes the explosive opening of the next installment. The story within the over arching seasonal narrative wraps at the end of the second episode and we're on to the next locale. Production values are high, way beyond the cheesy shortcuts of direct-to-DVD action fare. Excellent use of mostly Hungarian and South African locations to mimic  global hotspots like Mogadishu, Nairobi, Kosovo, Mumbai, etc. Constant references to persons and places making the world a scary place right now add authenticity and challenge your geographical knowledge. The men are all real men and the women are all hot. This is action fantasy. Warning: Not family fare. Some brief scenes border on soft care.

I liked the first season quite a bit but this one seems to be a bit thinner than its predecessor.

Here's the scoop. The boys are back but with a new commanding officer (Rhona Mitra) and in a new location (South Africa). Four nuclear triggers have gone missing and a wealthy industrialist (Charles Nance) figures to use them as a threat to give Africa back to its natives. Meanwhile, a renegade operative is out to kill Sgt. Stonebridge after he was forced to kill the operative's brother when said brother pops a cork during a training exercise and begins killing his fellow trainees.

As I mentioned above the script seemed much thinner and lazier to me than in the first season. The writers fleshed things out with a lot of fire fights and hand to hand. The storyline is decent enough but it seemed a long way around to get where you're going. Plus, I like when these types of films use current technology to help them do their thing. The Bourne films were good at this. Here, somehow, it seemed too lazy and pat. They always had closed circuit TV to get info when they needed it and facial recognition was always really quick and spot on. The 2 key guys recover way too quickly from injuries and beatings and their headquarters, which were blown up, seem to have been restored too quickly. In light of the fact that their department's future was in serious doubt makes that all the more curious.

While this series has some glaring flaws and inconsistencies, that doesn't stop me from loving it. Let's start with the problems. Virtually every episode has one or more shoot-'em-up scenes with a massive body count, often of a dozen or more, and the sequences are pretty much set up like the violent shooting video games that young people have been playing for the past 20 or more years (I assume it's thus being marketed to that audience). Also, there isn't much analysis of why the bad guys are THAT bad, and sometimes, the rationale can be pretty superficial - I thought this to be particularly true at the end of (North American) season two, though I'll offer no spoilers on that one. Finally, unlike, say, Game of Thrones, where "anyone" can die, we can feel pretty confident that the two protagonists are going to make it to the end of the season, so long as there are no problems with their contracts, or they don't drop this show to take on something even bigger (and this one is pretty big, mind you).

Now, on the positive side... It goes without saying that Philip Winchester as Stonebridge and Sullivan Stapleton as Damien Scott are absolutely inspired. This is a buddy show, and these two guys are perfect buddies in that time-honoured tradition - with Winchester the "straight" guy and Stapleton the "loose (but dependable) cannon." They are also allowed at times (never for long) to have fun, and that element of intermittent delight was never written into the (earlier) UK season one (see my review of Chris Ryan's Strike Back). As to the production budget, it's obviously of good size, and thus we are able to travel the world (literally) with our protagonists. The screenwriting is excellent, the dialogue regularly engaging and deeply insightful, and the soundtrack/music are state of the art - outstanding. The same goes for the cinematography/camerawork, and the Blu-Ray picture is crisp and clear (you will not get that in UK season one, which is equivalent in terms of the competency of its actors, but produced on a much lower budget). Finally, it should be obvious from what I have written that these are characters you will care about (Mr. Stapleton sustained a head injury in Thailand earlier this year, and I'm concerned for him in the same way I would be for a friend).... but, more than that, these are characters who will teach you about yourself and the world: that is, they often face moral dilemmas, and are able to handle them in such a way that it is necessary to reflect on one's own life and choices, and how we might measure up in the same circumstances. The moral dilemmas feel VERY real - they are not staged or strained, and the actors are at that highest level, in that they have the ability to take us to the unexplored places of our own lives.

In conclusion... this series (originating in the UK) was a surprise. I hadn't heard anything about it until seeing the first season blu-ray on display one day while shopping. So I'll rate this one my "lucky find of the year." (Last year, my lucky find was Orphan Black, so I think my standards are reasonably high.) If you can handle the extremely high body count, you will be rewarded with every episode. There is very little time wasted at any point in this series. And... season two stands up perfectly well to season one. Two great years and counting.

Sorry for the confusing headline but if you don't know, this second season of 'Strike Back' (SB going forward) from Cinemax is actually season three overall of the series which was originally called "Chris Ryan's Strike Back" based on the novels of the same that aired on Sky1 in the U.K.  I still haven't seen the first series (season) that starred Richard Armitage ("MI-5"/"Spooks," others...) however, his character was unceremoniously murdered by terrorists in the opening scene of Cinemax's first season of the show so even though it's not technically necessary to have the UK series, it does all tie in together.

I thoroughly enjoyed Cinemax's first season of SB for all of its action, generally strong writing for an action series and great plot-twists that rivaled the best of '24.'  Truthfully speaking, SB is big, dumb, guilty-pleasure fun with plenty of sex, violence and foul language to appeal to the purile teenager in all of us while at the same time providing compelling story arcs.

That being said, I was rather disappointed in CInemax's SB season two.  Don't get me wrong, it was still fun but it really didn't go anywhere and the motivations for the main villain were stupid as to seem like they ran out of ideas and just went for Bond Villain motivations.

****MINOR SPOILER ALERT*** (This is revealed in the first episode)

Another thing that really bugged me was that it was obvious that they didn't know what to do with the character of Stonebridge's wife so they just... y'know... got rid of her... in the most bizarre of circumstances that wind up being a major plot point throughout the whole season.  It was a very convoluted and unnecessary sub-plot that was pretty cheap and obvious to anyone who was paying attention and it didn't even have a decent resolution.  NOTE TO THE WRITERS: if you're going to off a character because they don't fit in to where the show and the rest of the characters are heading, don't drag it out.  Just off them and be done with it.  This show only has ten episodes per season, already.

Overall, there was a lot more that they could have done with Cinemax's SB season two but they wasted time on pointless sub-plots.  The mysteries surrounding Damien Scott's past are a goldmine that can go any direction and Stonebridge's character is being woefully neglected as far as development is concerned.

Still, Cinemax's SB season two was fun despite my complaint and I wouldn't kick it out of the DVR for eating crackers (and I gladly pre-ordered this set).

Of course the video and the audio quality of the set is fantastic on Blu-ray, especially the DTS HD-MA audio track. It's feature-film quality across the board.  The only complaint I have is that unlike Cinemax's SB season one, this is Blu-ray and Digital Copy ONLY and there are no DVDs.  Not suggesting that  I really care because I don't use them for anything other than coasters but I paid the same price for season two as I did for season one and got less less product.  Just sayin'... no big deal really.

First off: love the show, but I can't rate every show I love with five stars.  I'm writing this review based on two seasons, actually: seasons 1 and 2 (not counting season 0, and yes, I'm going for an inside joke here).

I call it a graphic novel because that is the level of realism.  Other reviewers have spoken positively of the pace and style of the storylines, and I agree with them.  The series is engrossing.  The female characters are at the same time male- and feminist-fantasy icons.  I have known more than my share of special-ops types and none of them are female--and if they were, they wouldn't be seen traipsing around in hip-huggers and low-cut shirts.  NOTE TO PRODUCERS: I'm not asking for a change!  But seriously...  It was sort of like when *The Unit* jumped the shark with the pretty blonde "operative."  And as for the male-fantasy part, Scott (the character, that is) speaks for himself.

In a few years, things may change with the real-life equivalents of the female characters (the changes have already started to start, but there is no prayer of there being a female special-ops major to be found at this writing, let alone a special-ops female colonel).  But for now, there's clearly a feminist fantasy at work here.

So, if like me, you like graphic novels on TV, you'll love this.  If you want a realistic special-ops story ... not quite so much.

This is much in the same as the first season. The differences, Scott and Stonebridge are comfortable as partners once Stonebridge insists on rescuing Scott and they get back together.

Stonebridge starts out as an instructor of the SAS, cozily (unhappily?) holed up with his wife, who is bitter that she's miscarried, and seems to blame that on her husband in some way. He deals with this the same way he does everything, he avoids dealing with it. When she is killed by a revenge seeking soldier, he finally shows emotion. Then he shuts down, saying all the right things to make it back to section 20.

Well, we all know that the kind of soldier he is belongs out in the field. He will only truly be happy if he is on a mission, taking orders. It is more the adrenaline of the fight that makes his blood sing than any other kind of passion.

Scott and Stonebridge reunite and take their sprawling, brawling mission across Africa, spraying bullets like rain. This time they are less alone than last season. Richmond has been allowed into the field, and Baxter, a young fresh faced kid, and the new boss-lady, Dalton, every bit as unlikable as Col. Grant was. Sinclair makes a few forays out of the command center, ultimately resulting in his death. There is naturally a CIA operative who is manipulating things, twisting the knife in Scott to get her way over and over.

There is the ultimate bad guy, Conrad Knox, wealthy, zipping down a path of destruction that is both public and private, a nasty mercenary who seems fed up, and the crazy, revenge seeking tormenter who killed Mrs Stonebridge to harass the team all the way across multiple countries.

They escape from one impossible situation after another. There are some crazy battles. Watching the two main men fight is pretty intense. There is a purity to their purpose. Some of the others, there is a deliberate viciousness, whereas the feel from Scott and Stonebridge is almost noble, if killing so many could even be called noble.

The women are again without mercy, and most of Scott's hookups you would hesitate to turn your back on even to pull up your shorts.

If you are looking for adventure, firefights, a series where only soldiers understand what is in the mind of soldiers, but others try to intrude and force their will time after time... then this is your adventure series. Set in the midst of incredible scenery, with all involved struggling for survival, this is definitely it. Enjoy.

STRIKE BACK is so prolific with its nude scenes, even the showmakers of GAME OF THRONES are awestruck. Just goes to show that, 'neath all that placid tea-drinking and scone-munching, the Brits flaunt quite the salacious streak. But gratuitous nekkidness aside, STRIKE BACK also rewards the viewer with gritty character development, a runaway train of a narrative, and, of course, the explosive, explosive gunplay. And with its secretive counter-terrorist task force deployed on a globetrotting pace, you may even soak up culture and end up a worldlier person.

STRIKE BACK is the only reason I keep Cinemax. Season 2 (or Series 3, if you're in the UK) offers ten more episodes and, at the start, shuffles the make-up of Section 20. Sgt. Stonebridge (Philip Winchester, a Yank actor posing as a Brit) is off the team, having opted for assignment on British soil to be near his wife. Nowadays, Stonebridge is a training officer at the local S.A.S. Training Camp. Or as one of his mates mockingly addresses him: "Mr. Stonebridge, desk jockey."

This leaves Sgt. Damian Scott (Sullivan Stapleton, an Aussie posing as a Yank) as Section 20's primary field agent. And when Damian is taken prisoner during a soured ops, who else but Stonebridge gets tapped for a bit of a rescue? I guess I can encapsulate stuff and just say that, this time out, Section 20 targets a hijacked set of nuclear triggers. But that's doing a disservice to the show. These ten new episodes make up another thrilling season. There are twists and turns and setback after setback, and, early on, a stroke of tragedy that turns the tables on the Scott/Stonebridge dynamics. Season 2 finds the formerly by-the-book Stonebridge suddenly the loose cannon of the bunch, and the disaffected American, Scott, now the steadying presence. However, in keeping with his bad boy image, light is shed on Scott's murky past, particularly his shady affiliation with the CIA. As always, STRIKE BACK excels in showcasing the emotional toll the brutal missions exact on these super-soldiers. Winchester and Stapleton are so good. They sink into the skins of their characters. Even their silences convey depths of meaning. On the fun side, their tough guy banter is endlessly entertaining.

If you've been a fan of stay-at-base tech support, Sgt. Richmond (Michelle Lukes), know that she now deploys to the field more. And, as it turns out, she's a cool-headed badasss. Section 20 is also assigned a prickly new director. Thankfully, British diplomat Rachel Dalton (played by Rhona Mitra, goddess of cheekbones), looks as good in a military uniform as did the late Colonel Eleanor Grant. Charles Dance - whom I mostly know from GAME OF THRONES and from the bad guy in THE LAST ACTION HERO - is wicked good as this season's central villain.

The body count meter keeps breaking down on this show. Even Jack Bauer is impressed. It'll be a challenge coming up with a similarly scaled threat for Section 20 to combat next. This unit has already thwarted a biological attack and now nuclear winter. What could top those? What's more daunting? I can't wait to find out.

MINOR SPOILERS:

Truth be told, I actually preferred last season to this.  Left out of my title header was well thought out plot.
I simply couldn't relate to the concept of a billionaire Englishmen who considered himself an "adopted son of Africa", chucking it all under the guise of making Africa a nuclear power.  I also thought that the finale was a little anti-climatic.

So why the *5 you ask?  Really, a rhetorical question.  If one is "jonesing" for a serialized action series (MA rated or otherwise), there are few other options, even factoring in programming from Canada, UK and Australia.

I am curious to see what direction the next season takes and while my personal preference goes towards last season, this season still gets my highest recommendation for fans of the genre.
